default2.5
default              
defaultDefra wants to see a competitive farming industry that faces less red tape, takes advantage of export opportunities and is less reliant on public subsidy.  Over the next seven years the UK 
defaultis expected to 
defaultreceive 
defaultabout 
default£17.8 billion under Pillar 1 on direct subsidies and £1.84 billion under Pillar 2 on the environment and rural development (subject to confirmation
default, both figures are 2011 prices
default). Where Defra has greater discretion on how CAP money is spent, we need to make sure it is spent efficiently, in the right places and where it adds greatest public value. Whatever decisions are taken on the implementation of the CAP, and specifically in relation to the potential transfer of money from Pillar 1 to Pillar 2, the majority of CAP payments will still be to farmers through 
defaultthe 
defaultPillar 1 
defaultDirect P
defaultayment
default Scheme
