default&#xa0;
default3.1
default              
defaultWhile 
defaultDefra
default felt the Commission had identified the right challenges in its Communication of 2010 – the need to increase agricultural productivity to meet growing world demand for food and at the same time reduce environmental impact – we were disappointed at the lack of ambition the Commission showed in the package of CAP proposals published on 12 October 2011. The UK did not see how the initial proposals would address the objectives the Commission had identified.
default&#xa0;default3.2
default              
defaultThis was the first CAP Reform to be co-decided with the European Parliament (EP), following the entry into force of the Treaty on the Functioning of the E
defaulturopean 
defaultU
defaultnion
default (Lisbon Treaty). 
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default              
defaultAfter months of detailed negotiations, the Council of Ministers, European Parliament (EP) and European Commission agreed a new CAP deal in principle in June 2013.
default 
default&#xa0;
default3.4
default              
defaultAt the time of the June deal, MEPs had insisted that agreement was still outstanding on elements of the CAP package linked to the EU Budget agreement in February 2013.  These outstanding issues were discussed and resolved with minimal changes to the CAP package in September 2013. The EP is now expected to vote on the CAP package in mid-November followed by final approval from the Council of Ministers in December 2013. 
default&#xa0;
default3.5
default              
defaultCAP implementing legislation will follow from the European Commission; to be agreed by in the first half of 2014.  This legislation will provide the detail to the main CAP regulations agreed this year. The full CAP package will take effect from 2015
default 
defaultwith the 
defaultsCMO
default coming fully into effect before then in 2014.  A transitional regulation for 2014 is being agreed in parallel with the main CAP regulations and will also be subject to final approval in December 2013.
default&#xa0;
default3.6
default              
defaultThe UK negotiated hard to secure a final outcome on the CAP regulations that overall was a significant improvement on the Commission’s original proposals. However, it is still very disappointing and does not move CAP anything like as far as we’d have wanted in the direction of reform.  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default4.1
default              
defaultMany scheme rules are set out in the EU regulations and we have no choice other than to follow them.  However there are aspects where we have options on how we implement elements of CAP. Where there is scope to do so, 
defaultDefra 
defaultis aiming 
defaultto implement the new CAP in England
default in ways which are simple, affordable and effective
default. Simplicity for 
defaultthose 
defaultappl
defaultying 
defaultfor CAP funding as well as for our delivery bodies administering the systems will not only be more efficient but will also 
defaulthelp reduce
default the risk of disallowance. 
defaultDefra’s
default approach to implementing the revised CAP is intended to meet wider government better regulation commitments and to minimise as much as possible the potential burdens on CAP customers.
default&#xa0;
