default5.2
default              
defaultOur approach addresses 
defaultrecommendations from the Farm Regulation Task Force.
default For example, we have been working closely with the farming organisations, our delivery bodies and other interested parties on the development of proposals on the implementation of the Direct Payment Schemes and the new environmental land management schemes.
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default              
defaultThe openness of our approach does not mean everyone with an interest in the new 
defaultCAP will agree on everything. There will undoubtedly be strong and divergent views, as there were during the negotiations. There will be difficult decisions. Some elements of the new CAP will increase complexity and it is important that we minimise these where we can.  
default&#xa0;
default5.4
default              
defaultThe Secretary of State, other Ministers, and officials have engaged directly and frequently with the farming industry and other interested groups. Defra has held several events in recent months, attended by Ministers, to hear first-hand from a broad range of 
defaultinterested groups on their thoughts about CAP implementation
default. These events have been informative and have helped to shape the formal public consultation
default. For example, 
defaultMinisters took account of views 
defaultexpressed 
defaultin deciding to consult on as much of the CAP package as possible at this stage, and in framing the consultation questions. 
default&#xa0;
default5.5
default              
defaultCAP touches a wide range of agricultural, rural, environmental and other interests. Defra and its delivery bodies are working closely together to ensure a coherent and consistent approach to engaging with this wide range of interested groups and individuals, drawing on the expertise and understanding shared between the organisations. At a practical level, the relevant teams meet monthly to plan activity. 
default&#xa0;
default5.6
default              
defaultWe will consult formally on the implementation of CAP shortly. Our intention is to make the consultation as comprehensive as possible to help interested parties to reach an informed view on interrelated issues. In some cases the Government already has a clear view on the way forward, or has already had to make decisions due to the long lead 
defaulttime for implementing aspects of the schemes or the need for farmers to have certainty. In these cases the consultation document will set out what we have decided. In other areas we will be seeking views in order to make the best informed choices.
default&#xa0;
default5.7
default              
defaultThere are some constraints that affect the timetable for consultation. We need to notify the Commission formally by 31 December 2013 on whether and to what extent we wish to transfer funds from the CAP budget for direct payments (Pillar 1) to fund rural development (Pillar 2), which is part of this consultation. 
default&#xa0;
default5.8
default              
