default7.1
default              
defaultThe Single Common Market Organisation (
defaultsCMO
default) regulation lays down rules for the common organisation of agricultural markets. Market measures set out in the 
defaults
defaultCMO
default regulation include the tools used to provide a safety net at times of market crisis inside the EU
default,
default trade and competition rules, quota systems, specific marketing standards that apply to certain sectors and/or products, individual aid schemes and the promotion of producer organisations 
default(POs) 
defaultand inter-branch organisations
default (IBOs) that operate more widely than POs by working along the supply chain
default. 
defaultThe safety net includes 
defaultintervention, export refunds, private storage aid and the provision of a new crisis reserve
default. T
defaulthe quota systems in the sugar and wine sectors will now be in place for extended periods
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default7.2
default              
defaultIn most cases, the new 
defaultsCMO
default regulation updates existing provisions rather than representing a radical reform, however several of the changes that have been made
default rollback previous CAP reforms and went against the Lisbon Treaty in transferring additional powers to the EP. At Agriculture Council in June
default 2013
default the UK and Germany could not support the 
defaults
defaultCMO
default regulation due to the amendments that had been made in order to reach a compromise with the European Parliament. The UK and Germany therefore abstained in the 
defaultsCMO
default vote to enable agreement on the overall CAP package.
