default8.11
default              
defaultThe new CAP includes a 
defaultprovision that 30% of a farmer’s
default Direct Payment should be conditional on them meeting certain criteria intended to be beneficial to the wider environment. This is referred to as “greening”. Ministers have decided that the broad approach to greening in England should be to adhere to the 
defaultagricultural practices 
defaultset out in the 
defaultDirect
default Payments Regulation and 
defaultis
default announced as part of the consultation package
default.
default&#xa0;
default8.12
default              
defaultThere has been an appetite from stakeholders for early clarity on the approach to greening. Arable farmers need the information as early as possible so that they can begin to make crop plans for the 2015 calendar year. Stakeholder organisations wished for clarity to help put into context their views on such issues as the level of financial transfer between pillars of the CAP and the approach that should be taken to successor 
defaultagri
default-environment schemes.
default&#xa0;
default8.13
default              
defaultTwo b
defaultroad approaches to greening are
default realistically
default 
defaultpossible
default:
default the one where we adhere to the 
defaultspecified agricultural practices
default, or an
defaultother
default based on the 
defaultoption 
defaultto implement greening through a 
defaultN
defaultational Certification Scheme that includes additional measures
default that are equivalent 
defaultto the 
defaultspecified agricultural practices
default. 
defaultMinisters are minded not to choose 
defaultthe second approach because, although it has the potential to bring enhanced environmental benefit, 
defaultwe
default could only do this at increased cost and increased risk
default. 
defaultThere would be increased costs to farmers who chose the equivalent measures, increased implementation costs and delivery risk to delivery agencies and increased risk of disallowance as we moved away from the basic model which we expect to be implemented elsewhere in 
defaultthe EU. Set against this we consider
default that the additional environmental benefits might be small in the context of a Certification Scheme in which farmers were able to choose simpler and cheaper alternatives and so where uptake of the more beneficial options might be low.
default&#xa0;
default8.14
default              
defaultT
defaulthis approach is consistent with the Government’s view that it is Pillar II of the CAP, not Pillar I initiatives such as greening, which provid
defaultes the optimum mechanism to deliver
default the majority of environmental outcomes from English farmland.
